04658nam a22006375i 9780231506526DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979967580  a97802315065267 a10.7312/edwa131782doi  a(DE-B1597)458827  a(OCoLC)213305960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a821/.72231 aEdwards, Pamela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Statesman's Science :bHistory, Nature, and Law in the Political Thought of Samuel Taylor Coleridge /cPamela Edwards. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: The Politics of Reputation, or, the Myth of a Modern Apostate -- tChapter 1. Romantic Radicalism -- tChapter 2. Attacking the State -- tChapter 3. Defending the Constitution -- tChapter 4. Liberty and Law -- tChapter 5. Morality and Will -- tChapter 6. Science and Nature -- tChapter 7. History and Life -- tChapter 8. Defending the Church -- tChapter 9. Attacking the Doctrine -- tConclusion. Regulating the Body Politic -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAuthor of "Kubla Khan" and the epic "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner," Samuel Taylor Coleridge is remembered principally for his contributions as a romantic poet. This innovative reconsideration of Coleridge's thought and career not only demonstrates his importance as a philosopher but also recovers romanticism as both an aesthetic and a political movement. Pamela Edwards radically departs from classic theories of Coleridge's development and reads his writing within the framework of a constantly shifting political and social landscape. Drawing on the ideology, rhetoric, and institutional theory at the turn of the late British Enlightenment, Edwards unearths the fundamental continuities in Coleridge's writing during the revolutionary period of 1794 to 1834, paying particular attention to the rhetoric of Coleridge's pamphlet and miscellaneous writings, the journalism of the Napoleonic years, his philosophical and ultimately political treatises within the contexts of his notebooks and letters, and his readings and intellectual friendships. What emerges is a clearer understanding of Coleridge's political philosophy and his contributions to the origins and ideology of British Liberalism. Coleridge's interest in history, nature, and law as inherently interconnected projects producing an ideal or scientific reading of society reveals a developed progressive social and cultural state theory anchored in individual conscience, moral autonomy, and a civic and participatory human agency. If the Statesman could understand and finally master this scientific view of the world, he would be able not only to adjust political and social institutions to comprehend the historical contingencies of the moment but to see through the problem of the moment to the dynamic of change itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/edwa1317840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231506526423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231506526/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE